"# Chapter 5 — BASIC and the home-computing era

BASIC was designed at Dartmouth College by John Kemeny and Thomas
Kurtz, first running in 1964. The name stood for Beginner's
All-purpose Symbolic Instruction Code. The idea: a programming
language simple enough that students in any discipline could use
computers.

BASIC became the language of the home-computing era. Almost every
early home computer booted directly into a BASIC prompt. Millions of
kids learned to program in BASIC as their first language, on Apple
IIs, Commodore 64s, Atari 800s, ZX Spectrums, TRS-80s, and dozens of
others.

Motoi's persona doctrine specifically remembers this era. A lot of
today's programmers of a certain age started here.

## Dartmouth BASIC

Kemeny and Kurtz wanted computing to be a fluent tool for
non-specialists. Dartmouth put a large time-sharing system (the
Dartmouth Time-Sharing System, DTSS) on campus. BASIC was the
language most students used to talk to it.

The original Dartmouth BASIC had:
- Line numbers (each line prefixed by a number, used for GOTO
  targets).
- Simple types (numbers and strings).
- `IF/THEN` conditionals.
- `FOR/NEXT` loops.
- `GOSUB/RETURN` subroutines.
- `PRINT` for output, `INPUT` for reading from the user.

A simple Dartmouth BASIC program:

```
10 PRINT \"WHAT'S YOUR NAME\"
20 INPUT N$
30 PRINT \"HELLO, \"; N$
40 END
```

Not fancy. Runs. Kid types it, runs it, sees their name back. That
immediacy is what made BASIC feel like the computer was a tool for
you, not a mystery for engineers.

## The home-computer BASICs

When home computers arrived in the late 1970s, they needed a language
in ROM that the machine would boot into. BASIC was chosen almost
universally because:
- It was simple enough to implement in ~4-16 KB of ROM.
- It was familiar to hobbyists.
- It didn't require compilation — you could interpret it directly.

The famous ones:

- **Microsoft BASIC** (Bill Gates and Paul Allen, 1975, for the
  Altair 8800). This was the first Microsoft product. Later
  Microsoft BASIC variants shipped in the Apple II (as Applesoft
  BASIC), the Commodore 64, the TRS-80, and many more.

- **Applesoft BASIC** (Apple II family, 1977 onwards) — a Microsoft
  BASIC with Apple II hardware support.

- **Commodore BASIC** (Commodore 64 and PET, and VIC-20). Written by
  Microsoft. Notoriously limited — no graphics or sound commands,
  which was a problem on machines with excellent graphics and sound
  chips. Programmers had to POKE values directly into hardware
  registers.

- **Atari BASIC** — for the Atari 800 and family. Slower than the
  Microsoft-derived competition. Had some interesting features.

- **BBC BASIC** (BBC Micro, 1981) — probably the best home-computer
  BASIC, written for the UK's Computer Literacy Project. Had
  structured programming features, a built-in assembler, and clean
  syntax.

- **ZX BASIC** (Sinclair machines). Used a token-based entry system
  where each keyword was one keystroke.

Each of these was BASIC in the sense of vocabulary, but they were
mutually incompatible. A program written for the C64 wouldn't run
on an Apple II without changes.

## The line-numbered style

Line numbers were part of BASIC because early BASIC interpreters
were line-editors. You typed a line with a number; the interpreter
stored it under that number. You typed a line with an existing
number; the interpreter replaced it. You typed a bare number; the
interpreter deleted that line.

The convention was to use line numbers spaced by 10 (10, 20, 30,
...) so you could insert new lines between existing ones (15, 25).
That's why so many BASIC programs count by tens.

Line numbers made GOTO the natural control-flow mechanism.

```
10 PRINT \"HELLO\"
20 GOTO 10
```

Type RUN and it prints HELLO forever. That's about as simple as
programming gets.

## Why BASIC mattered

BASIC put programming in front of millions of people who wouldn't
otherwise have encountered it. Alfred learned to program on a home
computer running BASIC. Many people who now work in software did.

BASIC was not elegant. It had globals everywhere. GOTO was
encouraged (Dijkstra's essay Chapter 7 of Book of Language Ancestors
was partly in response to BASIC and languages like it). Modularity
was minimal.

But BASIC was there. On every machine. Any kid who owned a home
computer could start typing programs. The learning curve was gentle.
The rewards were immediate. That accessibility was worth a lot,
even if the language taught some habits people had to unlearn later.

## What Motoi owes BASIC

The accessibility. The 'turn it on, type, run' feel. The idea that
a programming language should be simple enough that a beginner can
be productive on day one.

Also: the sense of a machine that talks back. BASIC's prompt was
present, immediate, ready. Motoi tries to have some of that
feeling. Fire up Motoi, get a prompt, do something.

## A tiny example

A BASIC-style number-guessing game in Motoi Scheme, imitating the
shape:

```
(define (guessing-game)
  (let ((secret (random-int 100)))
    (display \"I'm thinking of a number between 1 and 100.\") (newline)
    (let loop ((guesses 0))
      (display \"Your guess: \")
      (let ((guess (read-integer)))
        (cond
          ((= guess secret)
           (display \"You got it in \")
           (display (+ guesses 1))
           (display \" guesses!\") (newline))
          ((< guess secret)
           (display \"Higher.\") (newline)
           (loop (+ guesses 1)))
          (else
           (display \"Lower.\") (newline)
           (loop (+ guesses 1))))))))

(guessing-game)
```

That's the shape of a BASIC program on an old home computer, in a
Scheme-flavored dress. Guess, respond, loop. Simple. Satisfying.
This was what programming felt like for a lot of kids.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

BASIC was not a serious language for serious software. But it was
serious enough for one generation of kids to learn programming, and
that mattered more than the language's technical shortcomings.

Motoi wants to be that today. Small enough to fit on your machine.
Immediate enough that you can type something and see a response.
Warm enough that a kid feels welcomed. That is the Speak & Spell
principle, restated in code. BASIC did it for a generation. Motoi
tries to do it for the next.")
